This is the Documentation for creating a door using the newdoor file
 
	NOTE: Major revisions were made to this code on or about
	5/23/97. It should be backwards compatible with the
	exception that some of the messages were changed and block
	checks were added. The extra three arguments (mix1, mix2, and
	str7) are all optional but remember that you'll need
	place holders for any of them which precede ones you do
	want to use.

So you want to put a door in your castle, eh?  Well, this is how you do it.
 
Create a room or edit one already created.
 
Change the inheritance to: inherit DOORROOM;
 
Somewhere in the reset(), (if you want it to reset every time, put it
before your if (arg) return; line(s)), you must add the following
function:
 
        MAKE_DOOR(str1, str2, str3, str4, str5, int1, 
		int2, int3, str6, int4, mix1, mix2, str7);
 
I wrote it like this so you understand what types of values to use:
  string for str#, integer for int#, mixed for mix#.
 
		       ********************

str1: This is the door_type to which the door will respond.  Usually,
      a door is a door.  In this case, however, a door can be a window,
      a rockpile, a trapdoor, a casket, a closet, etc.  The door_type
      must be a ONE WORD string.  Else, your door may not work.
      Lets assume you want a "door".  The line should look like this
      now:
 
      MAKE_DOOR("door",
 
		       ********************

str2: This is the direction that the door exits this room in.  Let's
      choose northeast.
 
      MAKE_DOOR("door","northeast",
 
		       ********************

str3: Now this string is required to make sure the door actually goes
      somewhere.  You may have guessed it already.  Yes, this is the
      pathname for the room on the other side of the door.  If you have
      a room in mind,  then thats what you should insert here.  If you
      hadn't thought that far ahead, dont worry, just make up a file
      name for the next room and make a whole new room.  You'll have to
      do the same to that door as you do here, so be forewarned.  I call
      this value the partner_door string.
 
      MAKE_DOOR("door","northeast","players/you/room2",
 
		       ********************

str4: Next comes the door itself.  What does it look like?  What should
      players see if they look at it?  By the way, you should have mentioned
      that there is a door here in the room's description (unless you
      want it to be a secret, of course)!  How about a big blue door with
      a bronze bolt?  I always did like aliteration! Oh, if you pass 0
      for this argument, you'll get a default description. The default
      isn't exciting but rather just a basic description.
 
      MAKE_DOOR("door","northeast","players/you/room2",
                 "\
This door is big, blue, and on the left, there is a bronze bolt,\n\
with a padlock!",
 
*NOTE*: No, you do NOT have to put a carriage return (\n) at the end
        of your door description.  You are certainly welcome to, if you
        so chose.
 
		       ********************
 
str5: We said the door had a padlock?  then which key will work in it?
      Here's where you can set that.  I call this the key_code string.
      It can be pretty much any strange code you like, so have fun!  I
      do suggest you stick to one word, and no funny characters.  Please
      remember to use this same code when you make a key!  If you dont
      want to have a door that can be locked, then just set this string
      to " ".  (actually, it still doesn't matter what the code is.  More
      on that later).  Code, code,...  what should be the code?   I know!...
 
      MAKE_DOOR("door","northeast","players/you/room2",
                "\
This door is big, blue and on the left, there is a bronze bolt,\n\
with a padlock!",
                "test1",
 
		       ********************
 
int1: Now were're into the integers needed.  Those of you familiar with
      the old door-object might recognize these.  The first is the trigger
      for opening and closing the door.  I call it is_closed.  If
      is_closed = 1, then this statement is true, and the door is actually
      closed.  If is_closed = 0, then its a false statement, meaning that
      the door is open. Make sense?  I like starting with a nice,
      inviting, open door:
 
       MAKE_DOOR("door","northeast","players/you/room2",
                 "\
This door is big, blue and on the left, there is a bronze bolt,\n\
with a padlock!",
                 "test1", 0,
 
    You can use the defined values OPEN and CLOSED here, as well.

		       ********************
 
int2: Related to the is_closed integer is the is_locked integer.  Means
      about the same thing, except this one controls whether the door is
      locked or not.  Use 1 for true, 0 for false.   Oh, btw, These
      values (int1 and int2) will be true for the door every time there
      is a reset or shutdown. Thats why this whole thing has to go into
      the reset function in your room.  Why lock the door if its open?
      (actually i set things so that you can't lock an open door.  Please
      don't be contrary and set it anyway. Unforseen errors will probably
      occur, erasing all your files and crashing the mud! (Well, they
      could!)
 
      MAKE_DOOR("door","northeast","players/you/room2",
                "\
This door is big, blue and on the left, there is a bronze bolt,\n\
with a padlock!",
                "test1", 1, 0
 
    You can also use the defined values UNLOCKED and LOCKED here.

		       ********************
 
int3: What's left?  Why, the bit i was talking about earlier, the
      ability to lock the door!  I called it the can_lock integer.
      Again, 1 is true, the door can be locked and unlocked.  0 means
      false, not able to lock the door.  By setting this variable to 0,
      the key_code and is_lock items become unnecessary (except it'll
      mess up if you skip them).  I like having a lock... keeps out the
      unsavory types. :)
 
      MAKE_DOOR("door","northeast","players/you/room2",
                "\
This door is big, blue and on the left, there is a bronze bolt,\n\
with a padlock!", "test1", 1, 0, 1,
 
    You can also use the defined values NONLOCKABLE and LOCKABLE here.

		       ********************
 
str6: You will need to also pass the direction of the door from the
      _other_ room.  So in this example, the door in this room went
      northeast, so the door in the other room will go southwest.
      Simple eh?  Here is what your MAKE_DOOR command will look like:
 
       MAKE_DOOR("door","northeast","players/you/room2",
                 "\
This door is big, blue and on the left, there is a bronze bolt,\n\
with a padlock!", "test", 1, 0, 1, "southwest",
 
		       ********************
 
int4: You should set the percentage on a 1 to 100 scale of how hard it
      should be to pick this door.  If you do not want to worry about that
      set it to 0 and a default value will be set (currently 40%).
 
       MAKE_DOOR("door","northeast","players/you/room2",
                 "\
This door is big, blue and on the left, there is a bronze bolt,\n\
with a padlock!", "test", 1, 0, 1, "southwest", 65,
 
		       ********************
 
mix1: You can specify either a string or an array of strings which will
      act as alternate ids for this door. For example, you could refer to
      the door as the 'northeast door' or as 'glowing portal' or whatever
      you desire. Whatever you specify will be used to create the add_look()
      for the door and can be used by a player wishing to open, close, etc.
      the door. Let's create a couple of alternate names.

       MAKE_DOOR("door","northeast","players/you/room2",
                 "\
This door is big, blue and on the left, there is a bronze bolt,\n\
with a padlock!", "test", 1, 0, 1, "southwest", 65,
                 ({"glowing portal", "shining door"}),
 
		       ********************

mix2: You can also specify a string or an array of strings from which
      one will be given when ever someone listens to the door! I'll
      give a few mysterious noises to be heard by nosy players. Note
      that you can define your own query_door_sound() function as
      long as it accepts a string (what you specified for str2) and
      returns a string representing the sound that is heard.

       MAKE_DOOR("door","northeast","players/you/room2",
                 "\
This door is big, blue and on the left, there is a bronze bolt,\n\
with a padlock!", "test", 1, 0, 1, "southwest", 65,
                 ({"glowing portal", "shining door"}),
		 ({"moaning", "wailing" "screams"}),
 
		       ********************

str7: Lastly, if you want to be able to do some special processing of
      your own depending on what is done to the door, you can provide
      a function name to be called whenever your door is actually touched.
      The function will be passed whatever you specified as str2 as
      well as an integer corresponding to what happened to the door as
      a result of the action:
	-1 : Nothing done, door not touched.
	 0 : Nothing done, door was touched.
	 1 : Door changed state.
      You can used query_verb() to find out which function was actually 
      called. So, if you wanted to give someone a nasty electric shock
      when they opened a door, you could specify a function which checks
      for a positive return from the open() function on your door and
      let the player have it.

       MAKE_DOOR("door","northeast","players/you/room2",
                 "\
This door is big, blue and on the left, there is a bronze bolt,\n\
with a padlock!", "test", 1, 0, 1, "southwest", 65,
                 ({"glowing portal", "shining door"}),
		 ({"moaning", "wailing" "screams"}),
		 "zap_player");
 
		       ********************

     That's it for this room.  Now go edit the other room:
     "players/you/room2" and repeat this whole operation.  Hey, don't
     forget to change the partner_door and direction so that the player
     goes back to the correct room!   (you can have wierd jumps where
     you enter the door by going east, and have to go north to get back
     or something.  Do as Ye Will!).

     Also, don't forget to change the inherit line to DOORROOM!

General Functions:  (Not needed if you only want to *create* a door.)
 
status query_door_closed(string direction);
  Returns a 1 if the door is closed, 0 otherwise.

status query_door_locked(string direction);
  Returns a 1 if the door is locked, 0 otherwise.
 
int query_pick_chance(string direction);
  Returns the percentage required to pick the lock.
 
void force_unlock(string direction);
  Call this to force the door to unlock.
 
string query_code(string direction);
  Returns the key id which will unlock this door.

Good Luck!

